"""
Flow translations for 1 Enoch (chapters 1-108) -- complete text.
R.H. Charles 1912 translation (public domain).

Book of the Watchers (ch. 1-36): Theophanic introduction, nature's obedience
vs. human rebellion, the Watcher descent on Mount Hermon, the Nephilim,
forbidden knowledge (Azazel), the heavenly petition, God's four-angel judgment,
Enoch's commission, intercession for the Watchers, the throne theophany (ch. 14),
God's rebuke and demon origin (ch. 15), the cosmic journey, the prison of the
stars, the seven archangels, Sheol's four divisions (ch. 22), the Tree of Life
(ch. 24-25), Gehenna, and the Garden of Eden (ch. 32).

Parables / Similitudes of Enoch (ch. 37-71): The most christologically
significant section. The "Son of Man" figure (ch. 46, 48) parallels Daniel
7:13-14 and directly informs Jesus' self-designation. The "Head of Days"
(ch. 46-47) parallels the Ancient of Days in Daniel 7:9. Chapter 48's
pre-existence theology connects to John 1:1-3, Col 1:15-17. Chapter 51
affirms bodily resurrection from Sheol. Chapter 54 describes chains prepared
for Azazel's hosts (cf. Rev 20:1-3, 2 Pet 2:4). The oath of creation (ch. 69)
and Enoch's identification as the Son of Man (ch. 71).

Astronomical Book / Book of the Luminaries (ch. 72-82): The oldest section
of 1 Enoch (4QEnastr, early 2nd c. BC). Uriel guides Enoch through celestial
mechanics: the sun's six portals (ch. 72), the moon's phases (ch. 73-74),
the twelve winds (ch. 76), the 364-day solar calendar (ch. 82) -- the same
calendar followed by the Qumran community.

Dream Visions / Animal Apocalypse (ch. 83-90): Enoch's two dream visions.
The Animal Apocalypse (ch. 85-90) is an allegorical history from Adam through
the Maccabean period: bulls = patriarchs, sheep = Israel, wolves = Egypt,
the seventy shepherds (ch. 89:59, cf. Deut 32:8), and the white bull Messiah.

Epistle of Enoch (ch. 91-108): The Apocalypse of Weeks (ch. 93 + 91:12-17),
woe oracles against the wealthy and oppressors (ch. 94-105, anticipating
Matthew 23 and Luke 6), the birth of Noah (ch. 106-107), and concluding
exhortation (ch. 108).

Chapters: 108 | Verses: 1055 | Notes: ~130
"""

